Microalgae are a highly diverse group of unicellular photosynthetic prokaryotic and eukaryotic organisms [13,38]. Microalgae are considered sunlight-driven cell factories which can convert carbon dioxide into potential foods for human and animal consumption [39], and various types of renewable biofuels such as methane [39], biodiesel [40], and biohydrogen [41]. Microalgae are also important in biotechnological research due to their diversity, CO2 fixation capacity, and high biomass production capacity with lipid productivity for third generation biofuels [42]. Microalgae, either prokaryotic or eukaryotic are important to produce biofuel and many other byproducts (biochemicals, bioenergies, biohydrogen, etc.). Many companies are engaged in the mass cultivation of microalgae on a commercial scale and helping for the establishment of biobased economies [43]. The prokaryotic microalgae are also known as blue-green algae and cyanobacteria belong to the Cyanophyceae class (microalgae from this division can only fix atmospheric nitrogen independently and in association with other organisms). All eukaryotic microalgae are kept in other divisions of algal taxonomic classification i.e., Chlorophyceae (green algae), Phaeophyceae (brown algae), Rhodophyceae (red algae) and Bacillariophyceae (diatoms) (Fig. 1
                     ) [38]. With a distinct pool of morphological and physiological traits and growth behavior, this group has immense potential to resolve various complex environmental and socio-economic challenges (Table 1
                     ). Earlier studies have tested several microalgal species for bioenergy production and development of industrially relevant bioproducts while remediation of wastewater discharged from various domestic [44], agricultural [45], and industrial activities [9]. Empirical and long-term studies have identified various microalgae abundantly growing in sewage, particularly Chlorophyceae, as a dominant group in diversity and frequency compared to other classes, i.e., Cyanophyceae, Bacillariophyceae and Phaeophyceae [46,47]. Since the microalgae have been recognized and emerged as an ecofriendly tool for bioremediation of wastewater and bioenergy production [48–50], Chlorella, Scenedesmus, Chlamydomonas, Stigeoclonium (green algae), Oscillatoria (cyanobacteria), Euglena (Euglenophyta), Nitzschia, and Navicula (Bacillariophyta) and their different species are highly investigated [51–53] (see Fig. 1).

The microalgae grown in wastewater can be used directly (either as whole biomass or as lipid-extracted biomass, LEB) and indirectly (biofertilizers) for restoring degraded lands such as salt-affected lands [152,153], mine spoils [154,155], arid lands [156–160], and heavy metal polluted lands [29,161]. In addition, different forms of microalgae can be helpful in enhancing the fertility of degraded soils [162]. The main aim of restoring any degraded land is to increase desirable traits of the soil, like fertility and allied properties and decrease in undesirable traits, such as structural damage, chemical imbalance, and biological soil sickness, through various effective and sustainable means. The restoration efficacy of used amendments depends on two major factors (i) the chemistry of the amendment used and (ii) physical, chemical, and biological status of land being treated (Table 4
                     ). The direction and magnitude of change in quality of the degraded land with possible effects of microalgae biomass, LEB, and biofertilizers can be explained by estimating the increase in traits that make land healthy and decrease in traits that make land unfit for cultivation [163]. Mechanistically, change in soil physical properties due to application of microalgae has a great influence on soil's chemical and biological properties and vice versa (Fig. 2
                     ). For instance, an increase in soil flocculation due to microalgae secreted exopolysaccharides [159] improves soil aggregate stability, and infiltration rate [164]. The moment of water molecules takes excess salts (Na+, K+, Ca++), other pollutants and CO2 released by microbial activities, from the soil solution in the surface layers to the deeper depth [165]. This decrease in soil electrical conductivity increases soil biological activities and nutrient mineralization through microbial decomposition [166] of microalgae biomass [167,168]. Decline in soil stress with microalgae application increases the fraction of biological carbon (ratio of microbial biomass to organic carbon; also known as microbial quotient). This decreases the fraction of CO2 emission per unit of microbial biomass (also known as metabolic quotient) [166,168]. The microbial metabolic quotient is the rate of soil microbial respiration per unit of microbial biomass. It represents the capacity of soil microbes to utilize soil organic matter [169]. Microbial metabolic efficiency declines with increasing stress, and this is indicated by increasing metabolic quotients (microbial respiration per unit biomass, qCO2). Microbial metabolic quotient (qCO2) is an important soil health indicator to measure microbial C use efficiency. Soil carbon sequestration can be enhanced by increasing soil microbial biomass and C use efficiency, ultimately improving soil health [166]. As demonstrated in earlier studies, microbial biomass and biofertilizers quickly and remarkably change a broad spectrum of extracellular and intracellular soil enzymes that are involved in the degradation of organic matter and the mineralization of nutrients, including dehydrogenase, β-glucosidase, phosphatase, urease, peroxidase, etc. Application of microalgae, cyanobacteria and their biomass can substantially soil biological health through promoting nitrogen fixation, cycling of nutrients, and plant growth promotion. The impact of microalgae biomass, live cells and consortium of both microalgae and bacteria on soil microbial activities and soil biodiversity has been less investigated during restoration of degraded lands [26]. However, the following sections discuss the possible impacts of microalgae application on soil microbial and enzymatic activities in degraded lands.
